04850nam a22005775i 9780822392330DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20092009ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223923307 a10.1515/97808223923302doi  a(DE-B1597)554261  a(OCoLC)1224278090  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPN1993.5.I8bR275 2009 7aPER0040302bisacsh1 aRai, Amit S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aUntimely Bollywood :bGlobalization and India's New Media Assemblage /cAmit S. Rai. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2009] 4cÂ©2009  a1 online resource (316 p.) :b29 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 ae-Duke books scholarly collection00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: India and the New Nonlinear Media Assemblage -- tPart 1. Cinema Becoming New Media -- tOne. "First Day, First Show": Bollywood Cinemagoing and the New Sensorium -- tTwo. Contagious Multiplicities and the Nonlinear Life of the New Media -- tPart 2. Toward an Ontology of Media Durations -- tThree. "The Best Quality Cinema Viewing . . . Everywhere, Everytime": On the Malltiplex Mutagen in India -- tFour. "With You Every Moment in Time": On the Emergent Ittafaq (Chance) Assemblage -- tConclusion: Clinamedia -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aKnown for its elaborate spectacle of music, dance, costumes, and fantastical story lines, Bollywood cinema is a genre that foregrounds narrative rupture, indeterminacy, and bodily sensation. In Untimely Bollywood, Amit S. Rai argues that the fast-paced, multivalent qualities of contemporary Bollywood cinema are emblematic of the changing conditions of media consumption in a globalizing India. Through analyses of contemporary media practices, Rai shifts the emphasis from a representational and linear understanding of the effects of audiovisual media to the multiple, contradictory, and evolving aspects of media events. He uses the Deleuzian concept of assemblage as a model for understanding the complex clustering of technological, historical, and physical processes that give rise to contemporary media practices. Exploring the ramifications of globalized media, he sheds light on how cinema and other popular media organize bodies, populations, and spaces in order to manage the risky excesses of power and sensation and to reinforce a liberalized postcolonial economy.Rai recounts his experience of attending the first showing of a Bollywood film in a single-screen theater in Bhopal: the sensory experience of the exhibition space, the sound system, the visual style of the film, the crush of the crowd. From that event, he elicits an understanding of cinema as a historically contingent experience of pleasure, a place where the boundaries of identity and social spaces are dissolved and redrawn. He considers media as a form of contagion, endlessly mutating and spreading, connecting human bodies, organizational structures, and energies, thus creating an inextricable bond between affect and capital. Expanding on the notion of media contagion, Rai traces the emerging correlation between the postcolonial media assemblage and capitalist practices, such as viral marketing and the development of multiplexes and malls in India.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aGlobalizationzIndia. 0aMass mediazIndia. 0aMotion picture industryzIndiazBombay. 0aMotion picture industryzIndiazMumbai. 0aMotion pictureszIndia. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822392330zCo-access DOI